CARMEN XX.

There can be very little doubt that this ode is imitated from the Greek, though Dii. lenbr. denies it, as he generally does. It represents in heroic language a contest between Pyrrhus and a girl not named for the affections of the handsome Nearchus. The last two stanzas furnish a striking groupe for a picture. The passion of the jealous girl, and tho conscious pride of the beautiful boy, are happily painted. -
